initial_story: the aim of this paper is to provide a classification of multilingual andplurilingual electronic lexicographic resources which would enable, one the onehand, the implementation of quantitative and qualitative criteria to produce atypological taxonomy of lexicographical tools, such as dictionaries, as opposedto platforms and websites and, on the other, the distinction of multilingualand plurilingual resources in terms of their larger or lesser prototypingdegree. in addition to offering a thorough description of the differentresources, this paper also puts forward some parameters and typologicalproposals to define and demarcate a number of electronic resources,particularly multilingual dictionaries and portals, while also outlining, andeven questioning, the object of study of multilingual and plurilinguallexicography.
stories: The purpose of this paper is to develop a categorization system for multilingual and plurilingual electronic dictionaries and lexical platforms, enabling the application of quantitative and qualitative criteria to create a typological classification of lexicographic tools. This classification aims to distinguish between dictionaries, platforms, and websites, as well as identify multilingual and plurilingual resources based on their level of prototyping. The paper also provides a detailed description of the various resources, proposes parameters and typological frameworks to define and distinguish electronic resources, and explores the scope and boundaries of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.

This paper aims to design a categorization system for electronic dictionaries and lexical platforms that can handle multiple languages, allowing for the application of both quantitative and qualitative criteria to classify lexicographic tools typologically. The classification system will distinguish between dictionaries, platforms, and websites, and identify multilingual and plurilingual resources based on their level of development. The paper also provides a detailed overview of the various resources, proposes parameters and frameworks to define and distinguish electronic resources, and examines the scope and limits of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.

The proposed classification system will differentiate between dictionaries, platforms, and websites, and identify multilingual and plurilingual resources based on their level of development. The paper also provides a comprehensive overview of existing resources, outlines parameters and frameworks for defining and distinguishing electronic resources, and explores the scope and limitations of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.
